# Global Instructions (template)

Private, always-loaded rules for every Claude Code session. This is the "constitution" —
specifics about *who you are* and *how you work* live in the layered memory system below.
Replace the `<PLACEHOLDERS>` and delete what doesn't apply.

## Memory system (how it's wired)

Persistent memory: `<MEMORY_DIR>`  (e.g. `~/.claude/projects/<your-id>/memory/`)

- **Index** — `MEMORY.md` is the always-in-context table of contents. One line per memory, under 200 lines. It's how Claude knows what to read.
- **Memory files** — one fact per file, typed via frontmatter `metadata.type`:
  - `user` — who you are (role, expertise, preferences)
  - `feedback` — corrections/guidance on how Claude should work (include the *why* + *how to apply*)
  - `project` — ongoing work, goals, constraints not derivable from code/git
  - `reference` — pointers to external resources (URLs, dashboards, API endpoints)
- **On-demand files** — read only when the task calls for it (decisions, people, tools/APIs). Listed in the index.
- **Conversation log** — `conversations_index.md` (one line per past session) + `conversations/` (full logs, <30 lines each). Scanned only when prior work is referenced; never bulk-loaded.

Rules: "remember this" → save immediately to the right file. Never duplicate — update existing entries. Absolute dates only (e.g. `2026-06-18`, never "today"). Store *why*, not *what* — never store code patterns, git history, or anything discoverable by reading the project. Keep `MEMORY.md` under 200 lines.

## Model efficiency

Delegate everything that doesn't need top-tier reasoning to the cheapest capable subagent.
Reserve the expensive model for: ambiguous/strategic questions, architecture & tradeoff
decisions, complex multi-system debugging, and reviewing subagent output.

- **Mid-tier (e.g. Sonnet):** real code, non-trivial fixes/refactors/features, tests, configs, multi-file synthesis, project maps.
- **Cheap tier (e.g. Haiku):** broad file searches, mechanical bulk edits, extracting info from many files, filtering output.

Parallelize by default. Don't delegate trivial work (subagent boot ≈ 15–20k tokens).

## Token economy (value per token)

Biggest levers, in order:

- **Context firewall.** Every top-tier turn re-bills the whole conversation, so a bulk read is paid on every later turn, not once. Don't read large files/directories directly into the main context — delegate bulk reading/searching to a cheaper subagent that returns a distilled *conclusion*, not file dumps.
- **Cache discipline.** Prompt cache TTL ≈ 5 min. Batch independent tool calls into one turn; don't bloat always-loaded files mid-session or trigger denied-retry loops — each cache miss re-bills the whole prefix.
- **Cheap-first escalation.** Default to the cheapest plausible model and let the top tier *review*; only redo on verified failure.
- **Verify by stakes.** Cheap adversarial verifiers prevent expensive re-work — scale intensity to the stakes.
- **Measure.** A SessionEnd hook appends usage to a token ledger; review it (`/tokens`) and tune from data.

## Index-first exploration

Read the project's `CLAUDE.md` and target files directly before spawning agents. When delegating, tell the subagent to read the project's `CLAUDE.md` first — it cuts token usage substantially.

## Workflow discipline

- Use plan mode for non-trivial or multi-step work; confirm the approach before large or hard-to-reverse changes.
- Every project should have a `CLAUDE.md` at its root (file map, architecture, entry points, tech stack). If you touch a project that lacks one, create it (`/index`).
- Self-improvement: when you're corrected, capture it as a `feedback` memory so it persists.

## Security

- Review code/dependencies before installing or running them.
- Secrets live in `.env` files and are never committed or echoed into chat, logs, or memory.
- Confirm before outward-facing or hard-to-reverse actions.
